	                    <div class="dsq-comment-body" id="dsq-comment-body-2821089996">
	                        <div class="dsq-comment-header">
	                            <span class="dsq-comment-date">2016-08-04</span>
	                            <span class="dsq-commenter-name">weaverryan</span>
	                        </div>

	                        <div id="dsq-comment-message-2821089996" class="dsq-comment-message">
	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-2821089996" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Yo Vlad!</p><p>There is a slight difference between the Doctrine event subscriber and the event subscriber used by the JMSSerializerBundle. They philosophically do the same thing, but under the hood, Doctrine uses *its* event library, and JMS uses Symfony's event library. So the way that you wire them up is slightly different. So I don't think adding the "class" option works with Doctrine. BUT, Doctrine does support something slightly different, that does exactly this - it's called an entity listener. They're great, but the config is a little weird for me so I stick to subscribers. Check them out <a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2Fdocs.doctrine-project.org%2Fprojects%2Fdoctrine-orm%2Fen%2Flatest%2Freference%2Fevents.html%23entity-listeners%3A7x1xCr4cfKSks6XcMuoHuQG_wls&amp;cuid=1175718" rel="nofollow noopener">http://docs.doctrine-project.o...</a> and <a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2Fsymfony.com%2Fdoc%2Fcurrent%2Fbundles%2FDoctrineBundle%2Fentity-listeners.html%3AdJGwU9IY91WffVZUJ367n-NczHE&amp;cuid=1175718" rel="nofollow noopener">http://symfony.com/doc/current...</a></p><p>And yes to your code block - checking for !$entity-&gt;getPlainPassword() should do it - that's the bit I forgot!</p><p>Cheers!</p>
	                            </div>
	                        </div>
	                    </div>
	                </li>
